1 Introduction

In this section we explore the data to find and visualize patterns in the data set and how the features relate with one another. By the end of this section we should be able to judge how different features contribute towards predicting our target variable Revenue [True].

2 Load packages

library(ggplot2)
library(ggthemes)

3 Load dataset

Load the online shoppers intention dataset from the working directory into the dataframe df.

df=read.csv("online_shoppers_intention.csv", header = TRUE)

4 Feature exploration

ggplot(df, aes(x=Administrative, y=Administrative_Duration)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()

There is no strong co-relation between the no. of administrative pages visited and the duration.

ggplot(df, aes(x=Informational, y=Informational_Duration)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()

There is no strong co-relation between the no. of informational pages visited and the duration.

ggplot(df, aes(x=ProductRelated, y=ProductRelated_Duration)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()

There seems to be a strong co-relation between the no. of product related pages visited and the duration. This may be an important factor where independence of feature is a consideration.

Also, there are some clear outlier points and we may want to perform outlier handling for these points. We will re-plot the smoothening layer without the 2 outliers and check.

ggplot(df, aes(x=ProductRelated, y=ProductRelated_Duration)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth() +
  ylim(c(0,40000))
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Now we can see an almost linear relation between the features.

Next we will explore the relation of the features Administrative, Informational and ProductRelated count of pages in the session with the Revenue outcome.

# vector for customizing the label displayed for Revenue
custlabel <- c('TRUE' = "Revenue Generated", 'FALSE' = "No Revenue Generated")

# plotting the frequencies of informational pages per session for both FALSE and TRUE Revenue
ggplot(data = df, mapping = aes(x = Informational)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, color='green', fill='blue', alpha=0.5) +
  facet_grid(.~Revenue, labeller=labeller(Revenue = custlabel)) +
  labs(x = 'Informational Pages Visited', y = 'Frequency') +
  theme_clean()

# plotting the frequency distribution as % for informational pages per session for both FALSE and TRUE Revenue. e.g when Revenue is false, 80% of sessions had a zero informational page browsed
ggplot(data = df, mapping = aes(x = Informational)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1,aes(y = (..count..)/tapply(..count..,..PANEL..,sum)[..PANEL..] ), color='green', fill='blue', alpha=0.5) +
  facet_grid(.~Revenue, labeller=labeller(Revenue = custlabel)) +
  labs(x = 'Informational Pages Visited', y = 'Percentage') +
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent) +
  theme_clean()

# plotting the merged frequency distribution as % for informational pages per session and showing individual weights of FALSE and TRUE Revenue. e.g ~78% of all sessions had a zero informational page browsed 
ggplot(df, aes(x= Informational)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(y = (..count..)/sum(..count..), fill = Revenue), stat="count") +
  labs(x = 'Informational Pages Visited', y = 'Percentage') +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  theme_few() +
  theme(legend.position="top")

There does not look like any strong correlation with Revenue for informational pages.

# Frequency distribution of PageValues over sessions
ggplot(data = df, mapping = aes(x = PageValues)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10, color='green', fill='blue', alpha=0.5) +
  facet_grid(.~Revenue, labeller=labeller(Revenue = custlabel)) +
  labs(x = 'Average Page Value of Pages Visited', y = 'Frequency') +
  theme_clean()

ggplot(data = df, mapping = aes(x = PageValues)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10,aes(y = (..count..)/tapply(..count..,..PANEL..,sum)[..PANEL..] ), color='green', fill='blue', alpha=0.5) +
  facet_grid(.~Revenue, labeller=labeller(Revenue = custlabel)) +
  labs(x = 'Average Page Value of Pages Visited', y = 'Percentage') +
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent) +
  theme_clean()

Page Values are spread out over a large range but it looks like a good candidate as a categorical feature rather than continuous. So we will do feature engineering to create a new categorical feature - PageValuesCategory from Page Values.

We will bin the new category values as follows: if PageValues = 0 then ‘ZERO’ else if PageValues>0 and PageValues<10 then ‘LOW’ else if PageValues>=10 and PageValues<50 then ‘MEDIUM’ else if PageValues>=50 then ‘HIGH’

# summary of PageValues
summary(df$PageValues)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   0.000   0.000   0.000   5.889   0.000 361.764
# new categorical feature 
df$PageValuesCategory[df$PageValues==0]<-'ZERO'
df$PageValuesCategory[df$PageValues>0 & df$PageValues<10]<-'LOW'
df$PageValuesCategory[df$PageValues>=10 & df$PageValues<50]<-'MEDIUM'
df$PageValuesCategory[df$PageValues>=50]<-'HIGH'

# vector for customized label in plot
custlabel2 <- c('ZERO' = "PageValue=0", 'LOW' = "PageValue>0 and <10", 'MEDIUM' = "PageValue>=10 and <50", 'HIGH' = "PageValue>=50")

# for customized ordering of label in plot
df$PageValuesCategoryOrdered <- factor(df$PageValuesCategory, levels = c('ZERO','LOW','MEDIUM','HIGH'))

# plot of page value distribution % against the binned feature
ggplot(df, aes(x= Revenue, group=PageValuesCategory)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(y = ..prop.., fill = factor(..x..)), stat="count", show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_text(aes( label = scales::percent(..prop..),
                 y= ..prop.. ), stat= "count", vjust = -.5) +
  labs(y = "Percent") +
  facet_grid(~PageValuesCategoryOrdered, labeller=labeller(PageValuesCategoryOrdered = custlabel2)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  theme_few()

As seen in the plot there seems to be a very strong correlation between the categorized page value feature and Revenue target. e.g page value of zero has a false revenue of 96% and page value > 50 has 81% true revenue.

As seen in the data, the ‘Other’ visitor type does not provide any meaningful information and it seems appropriate that we treat them as New_Visitor for better categorization. So we will do feature engineering to convert Other to New_Visitor.

# converts Other to New_Visitor
df$VisitorType[df$VisitorType=='Other'] <- 'New_Visitor'

# % of frequency plot against the modified VisitorType for TRUE Revenue sessions
ggplot(df[df$Revenue==TRUE,], aes(x= VisitorType)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(y = (..count..)/sum(..count..)), fill = 'turquoise2', stat="count") +
  labs(x = 'VisitorType', y = 'Percentage of True Revenue') +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position="top")
